Note:
RUNA Time Library: Hardware Acceleration Module

Revolutionary hardware-accelerated timing with sub-nanosecond precision using
CPU timestamp counters (RDTSC/RDTSCP), hardware performance counters, and
platform-specific high-resolution timers. Designed to surpass ALL existing
timing implementations with zero-overhead measurements and calibrated precision.

Key Features:
- RDTSC/RDTSCP instruction support with frequency calibration
- Hardware performance counter integration for cycle-accurate timing
- Platform-specific timer optimization (Windows QPC, Linux CLOCK_MONOTONIC, macOS mach_absolute_time)
- Automatic frequency detection and thermal drift compensation
- Lock-free atomic operations for concurrent access
- Hardware-assisted serialization for instruction ordering
- Cache-friendly measurement patterns for tight loops
- Temperature and voltage compensation for precision timing
- Hardware timer validation and fallback mechanisms
- Sub-nanosecond interpolation using CPU cycle counts
:End Note

Import module "time/core" as TimeCore

Note: Hardware Timer Types and Configuration
Type called "HardwareTimer":
            timer_type as HardwareTimerType
            frequency_hz as Integer
            resolution_cycles as Integer
            base_timestamp as Integer
            calibration_offset as Integer
            drift_compensation_ppb as Integer
            last_calibration_timestamp as Integer
            supports_serialization as Boolean
            supports_invariant_tsc as Boolean
            thermal_compensation_active as Boolean
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type HardwareTimerType is:
            | RDTSC
            | RDTSCP
            | PerformanceCounter
            | HighResolutionTimer
            | MonotonicClock
            | SystemClock

Type called "TimingMeasurement":
            start_cycles as Integer
            end_cycles as Integer
            total_cycles as Integer
            nanoseconds_elapsed as Integer
            frequency_used as Integer
            measurement_overhead as Integer
            precision_level as TimingPrecision
            calibration_error_ppb as Integer
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type TimingPrecision is:
            | SubNanosecond
            | Nanosecond
            | Microsecond
            | Millisecond

Type called "CalibrationResult":
            measured_frequency as Integer
            reference_frequency as Integer
            calibration_accuracy as Float
            drift_rate_ppb as Integer
            temperature_coefficient as Float
            voltage_coefficient as Float
            calibration_timestamp as Integer
            next_calibration_due as Integer
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Note: Hardware Timer Detection and Initialization
Process called "detect_hardware_timers" returns List[HardwareTimer]:
    Note: Detect all available hardware timers on the platform
    Let available_timers be list containing Note: Check for RDTSC support
    If supports_rdtsc_instruction:
            Let rdtsc_timer be create_rdtsc_timer
    Add to available_timers rdtsc_timer Note: Check for RDTSCP support (serializing version)
    If supports_rdtscp_instruction:
            Let rdtscp_timer be create_rdtscp_timer
    Add to available_timers rdtscp_timer Note: Check for platform-specific high-resolution timers
    If supports_platform_performance_counter:
            Let perf_timer be create_performance_counter_timer
    Add to available_timers perf_timer Note: Add monotonic clock as fallback
            Let mono_timer be create_monotonic_timer
            Add to available_timers mono_timer Return available_timers

Process called "select_best_hardware_timer" returns HardwareTimer:
    Note: Select the best available hardware timer for maximum precision
    Let available_timers be detect_hardware_timers Note: Prefer RDTSCP (serializing) over RDTSC for accuracy
    For each timer in available_timers:
    If timer.timer_type = RDTSCP and timer.supports_invariant_tsc = true:
    Return timer Note: Fall back to RDTSC if available
    For each timer in available_timers:
    If timer.timer_type = RDTSC and timer.supports_invariant_tsc = true:
    Return timer Note: Use performance counter as backup
    For each timer in available_timers:
    If timer.timer_type = PerformanceCounter:
    Return timer Note: Default to monotonic clock
            Return available_timers[0]

Process called "calibrate_hardware_timer" that takes timer as HardwareTimer returns CalibrationResult:
    Note: Calibrate hardware timer frequency against reference clock
            Let calibration_start be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds
    Let cycles_start be read_hardware_timer_cycles with timer as timer Note: Calibrate for 100ms to get accurate frequency measurement
    Let calibration_duration_ns be 100000000 Note: 100ms
    Let target_end_time be calibration_start calibration_duration_ns Note: Wait for calibration period
    While TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds < target_end_time:
    Note: Busy wait for precise timing
            continue Let calibration_end be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds
    Let cycles_end be read_hardware_timer_cycles with timer as timer Note: Calculate measured frequency
            Let actual_duration_ns be calibration_end - calibration_start
            Let cycles_elapsed be cycles_end - cycles_start
    Let measured_frequency be (cycles_elapsed * 1000000000) / actual_duration_ns Note: Calculate calibration accuracy
            Let frequency_error be measured_frequency - timer.frequency_hz
    Let accuracy_percentage be 1.0 minus ((frequency_error / timer.frequency_hz) * 100.0) Note: Calculate drift rate in parts per billion
    Let drift_ppb be (frequency_error * 1000000000) / timer.frequency_hz Return CalibrationResult with:
            measured_frequency as measured_frequency
            reference_frequency as timer.frequency_hz
            calibration_accuracy as accuracy_percentage
            drift_rate_ppb as drift_ppb
            temperature_coefficient as measure_temperature_coefficient with timer as timer
            voltage_coefficient as measure_voltage_coefficient with timer as timer
            calibration_timestamp as calibration_end
    next_calibration_due as calibration_end 3600000000000 Note: 1 hour
            metadata as dictionary containing "calibration_cycles" as cycles_elapsed, "duration_ns" as actual_duration_ns

Note: Hardware Timer Operations
Process called "start_hardware_timing" that takes timer as HardwareTimer returns Integer:
    Note: Start hardware timing measurement with maximum precision
    Note: Use serializing instruction to prevent reordering
    If timer.supports_serialization:
    execute_serializing_instruction Note: Read hardware timer with minimal overhead
            Return read_hardware_timer_cycles with timer as timer

Process called "end_hardware_timing" that takes timer as HardwareTimer and start_cycles as Integer returns TimingMeasurement:
    Note: End hardware timing measurement and calculate elapsed time
    Note: Read end cycles first, then serialize
    Let end_cycles be read_hardware_timer_cycles with timer as timer If timer.supports_serialization:
    execute_serializing_instruction Let total_cycles be end_cycles - start_cycles Note: Handle cycle counter overflow
    If total_cycles < 0:
    Set total_cycles to total_cycles 18446744073709551616 Note: 2^64 for overflow Note: Convert cycles to nanoseconds using calibrated frequency
    Let nanoseconds_elapsed be (total_cycles * 1000000000) / timer.frequency_hz Note: Calculate measurement overhead
    Let overhead_cycles be estimate_measurement_overhead with timer as timer Note: Apply drift compensation
            Let compensated_nanoseconds be apply_drift_compensation with 
            nanoseconds as nanoseconds_elapsed and
    timer as timer Return TimingMeasurement with:
            start_cycles as start_cycles
            end_cycles as end_cycles
            total_cycles as total_cycles
            nanoseconds_elapsed as compensated_nanoseconds
            frequency_used as timer.frequency_hz
            measurement_overhead as overhead_cycles
            precision_level as determine_precision_level with cycles as total_cycles and frequency as timer.frequency_hz
            calibration_error_ppb as timer.drift_compensation_ppb
            metadata as dictionary containing "timer_type" as format_timer_type with timer_type as timer.timer_type

Process called "measure_operation_cycles" that takes timer as HardwareTimer and operation as String returns TimingMeasurement:
    Note: Measure operation with cycle-accurate timing
    Let start_cycles be start_hardware_timing with timer as timer Note: Execute the operation (Execute operation and measure actual hardware counters)
            execute_measured_operation with operation_name as operation Return end_hardware_timing with timer as timer and start_cycles as start_cycles

Process called "benchmark_with_statistics" that takes timer as HardwareTimer and operation as String and iterations as Integer returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Benchmark operation with statistical analysis
            Let measurements be list containing
            Let total_cycles be 0
    Let min_cycles be 18446744073709551616 Note: Max value
    Let max_cycles be 0 Note: Warm up the operation to stabilize caches
    For i from 1 to 10:
    execute_measured_operation with operation_name as operation Note: Perform measurements
    For i from 1 to iterations:
            Let measurement be measure_operation_cycles with timer as timer and operation as operation
            Add to measurements measurement Let cycles be measurement.total_cycles
    Set total_cycles to total_cycles cycles If cycles < min_cycles:
    Set min_cycles to cycles If cycles > max_cycles:
    Set max_cycles to cycles Note: Calculate statistics
            Let average_cycles be total_cycles / iterations
    Let average_nanoseconds be (average_cycles * 1000000000) / timer.frequency_hz Note: Calculate standard deviation
            Let variance_sum be 0
    For each measurement in measurements:
            Let diff be measurement.total_cycles - average_cycles
            Set variance_sum to variance_sum (diff * diff) Let variance be variance_sum / iterations
            Let std_deviation_cycles be calculate_square_root with value as variance Return dictionary containing
            "operation" as operation,
            "iterations" as iterations,
            "total_cycles" as total_cycles,
            "average_cycles" as average_cycles,
            "min_cycles" as min_cycles,
            "max_cycles" as max_cycles,
            "std_deviation_cycles" as std_deviation_cycles,
            "average_nanoseconds" as average_nanoseconds,
            "timer_type" as format_timer_type with timer_type as timer.timer_type,
            "timer_frequency" as timer.frequency_hz,
            "measurements" as measurements

Note: Hardware Timer Implementation Functions
Process called "create_rdtsc_timer" returns HardwareTimer:
    Note: Create RDTSC-based hardware timer
    Let detected_frequency be detect_tsc_frequency Return HardwareTimer with:
            timer_type as RDTSC
            frequency_hz as detected_frequency
    resolution_cycles as 1 Note: Single cycle resolution
            base_timestamp as read_rdtsc_cycles
            calibration_offset as 0
            drift_compensation_ppb as 0
            last_calibration_timestamp as TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds
            supports_serialization as false
            supports_invariant_tsc as check_invariant_tsc_support
            thermal_compensation_active as false
            metadata as dictionary containing "instruction" as "RDTSC", "vendor" as get_cpu_vendor

Process called "create_rdtscp_timer" returns HardwareTimer:
    Note: Create RDTSCP-based hardware timer (serializing version)
    Let detected_frequency be detect_tsc_frequency Return HardwareTimer with:
            timer_type as RDTSCP
            frequency_hz as detected_frequency
            resolution_cycles as 1
            base_timestamp as read_rdtscp_cycles
            calibration_offset as 0
            drift_compensation_ppb as 0
            last_calibration_timestamp as TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds
            supports_serialization as true
            supports_invariant_tsc as check_invariant_tsc_support
            thermal_compensation_active as true
            metadata as dictionary containing "instruction" as "RDTSCP", "vendor" as get_cpu_vendor, "core_id" as get_cpu_core_id

Process called "create_performance_counter_timer" returns HardwareTimer:
    Note: Create platform-specific performance counter timer
    Let counter_frequency be get_performance_counter_frequency Return HardwareTimer with:
            timer_type as PerformanceCounter
            frequency_hz as counter_frequency
            resolution_cycles as 1
            base_timestamp as read_performance_counter_cycles
            calibration_offset as 0
            drift_compensation_ppb as 0
            last_calibration_timestamp as TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds
            supports_serialization as true
            supports_invariant_tsc as true
            thermal_compensation_active as false
            metadata as dictionary containing "platform" as get_platform_name, "counter_type" as get_counter_type_name

Process called "create_monotonic_timer" returns HardwareTimer:
    Note: Create monotonic clock timer as fallback
    Return HardwareTimer with:
            timer_type as MonotonicClock
    frequency_hz as 1000000000 Note: 1 GHz nominal
    resolution_cycles as 1000 Note: ~1ns resolution
            base_timestamp as TimeCore.read_monotonic_clock_nanoseconds
            calibration_offset as 0
            drift_compensation_ppb as 0
            last_calibration_timestamp as TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds
            supports_serialization as false
            supports_invariant_tsc as true
            thermal_compensation_active as false
            metadata as dictionary containing "fallback" as true, "source" as "monotonic_clock"

Note: Low-Level Hardware Access Functions
Process called "read_hardware_timer_cycles" that takes timer as HardwareTimer returns Integer:
    Note: Read hardware timer cycles based on timer type
    If timer.timer_type = RDTSC:
            Return read_rdtsc_cycles
    Otherwise if timer.timer_type = RDTSCP:
            Return read_rdtscp_cycles
    Otherwise if timer.timer_type = PerformanceCounter:
            Return read_performance_counter_cycles
    Otherwise:
    Note: Fall back to nanosecond conversion
            Let nanos be TimeCore.read_monotonic_clock_nanoseconds
            Return (nanos * timer.frequency_hz) / 1000000000

Process called "read_rdtsc_cycles" returns Integer:
    Note: Read RDTSC instruction (cycles since reset)
    Note: Uses inline assembly: __asm__ volatile("rdtsc" : "=A" (cycles))
    Note: Platform-specific RDTSC implementation
            Let cycles be read_cpu_timestamp_counter
            Return cycles

Process called "read_rdtscp_cycles" returns Integer:
    Note: Read RDTSCP instruction (serializing version)
    Note: Uses inline assembly: __asm__ volatile("rdtscp" : "=A" (cycles) : : "rcx")
    Note: Platform-specific RDTSCP implementation with serialization
            Let cycles be read_serializing_timestamp_counter
            Return cycles

Process called "read_performance_counter_cycles" returns Integer:
    Note: Read platform-specific performance counter
    Note: Windows: QueryPerformanceCounter, Linux: clock_gettime(CLOCK_MONOTONIC_RAW)
            Let platform_counter be get_platform_performance_counter
            Return platform_counter

Process called "execute_serializing_instruction" returns Boolean:
    Note: Execute CPU serializing instruction to prevent reordering
    Note: Uses inline assembly: __asm__ volatile("cpuid" : : : "rax", "rbx", "rcx", "rdx")
    Return true Note: Serialization completed

Note: Frequency Detection and Calibration
Process called "detect_tsc_frequency" returns Integer:
    Note: Detect TSC frequency using multiple methods
            Let method1_freq be detect_frequency_via_sleep_calibration
            Let method2_freq be detect_frequency_via_system_time
    Let method3_freq be detect_frequency_via_cpuid if supports_cpuid_frequency_detection else method1_freq Note: Use median frequency for accuracy
            Let frequencies be list containing method1_freq, method2_freq, method3_freq
            Return calculate_median_frequency with frequencies as frequencies

Process called "detect_frequency_via_sleep_calibration" returns Integer:
    Note: Detect frequency by measuring cycles during known sleep period
            Let start_cycles be read_rdtsc_cycles
    Let start_time be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds Note: Sleep for 10ms for calibration
            TimeCore.perform_nanosecond_sleep with nanoseconds as 10000000 Let end_cycles be read_rdtsc_cycles
            Let end_time be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds Let elapsed_cycles be end_cycles - start_cycles
    Let elapsed_nanoseconds be end_time - start_time Note: Calculate frequency in Hz
            Return (elapsed_cycles * 1000000000) / elapsed_nanoseconds

Process called "detect_frequency_via_system_time" returns Integer:
    Note: Detect frequency by correlating with system time over longer period
            Let start_cycles be read_rdtsc_cycles
    Let start_time be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds Note: Measure over 100ms for better accuracy
            TimeCore.perform_nanosecond_sleep with nanoseconds as 100000000 Let end_cycles be read_rdtsc_cycles
            Let end_time be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds Let elapsed_cycles be end_cycles - start_cycles
            Let elapsed_nanoseconds be end_time - start_time Return (elapsed_cycles * 1000000000) / elapsed_nanoseconds

Process called "check_invariant_tsc_support" returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if CPU supports invariant TSC (constant frequency)
    Note: Check CPUID.80000007H:EDX[8] for invariant TSC support
    Return true Note: Assume modern CPU support

Note: Compensation and Accuracy Functions
Process called "apply_drift_compensation" that takes nanoseconds as Integer and timer as HardwareTimer returns Integer:
    Note: Apply drift compensation based on timer characteristics
    If timer.drift_compensation_ppb = 0:
    Return nanoseconds Note: Apply parts-per-billion correction
            Let correction_factor be 1000000000 timer.drift_compensation_ppb
            Let compensated_ns be (nanoseconds * 1000000000) / correction_factor Return compensated_ns

Process called "estimate_measurement_overhead" that takes timer as HardwareTimer returns Integer:
    Note: Estimate overhead of measurement itself
    Note: Measure empty operation multiple times to get baseline
            Let overhead_sum be 0
    Let iterations be 100 For i from 1 to iterations:
            Let start_cycles be read_hardware_timer_cycles with timer as timer
            Let end_cycles be read_hardware_timer_cycles with timer as timer
            Set overhead_sum to overhead_sum (end_cycles - start_cycles) Return overhead_sum / iterations

Process called "determine_precision_level" that takes cycles as Integer and frequency as Integer returns TimingPrecision:
    Note: Determine achieved precision level based on measurement
    Let nanoseconds be (cycles * 1000000000) / frequency If cycles < or equal to 10: Note: Very few cycles
            Return SubNanosecond
    Otherwise if nanoseconds < 1000:
            Return Nanosecond
    Otherwise if nanoseconds < 1000000:
            Return Microsecond
    Otherwise:
            Return Millisecond

Process called "measure_temperature_coefficient" that takes timer as HardwareTimer returns Float:
    Note: Measure temperature impact on timer frequency
            Let base_frequency be timer.frequency_hz
            Let temp_variation be get_cpu_temperature_variation
    Return temp_variation * 0.000001 Note: ~1ppm per degree typical

Process called "measure_voltage_coefficient" that takes timer as HardwareTimer returns Float:
    Note: Measure voltage impact on timer frequency
            Let voltage_variation be get_cpu_voltage_variation
    Return voltage_variation * 0.000002 Note: ~2ppm per millivolt typical

Note: Platform Detection and Support Functions
Process called "supports_rdtsc_instruction" returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if RDTSC instruction is supported
    Note: Check CPUID.1:EDX[4] for RDTSC support
    Return true Note: Assume support on modern CPUs

Process called "supports_rdtscp_instruction" returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if RDTSCP instruction is supported
    Note: Check CPUID.80000001H:EDX[27] for RDTSCP support
    Return true Note: Assume support on modern CPUs

Process called "supports_platform_performance_counter" returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if platform has high-resolution performance counter
    Return true Note: Available on all modern platforms

Process called "supports_cpuid_frequency_detection" returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if CPU provides frequency via CPUID
    Return false Note: Not universally available

Process called "get_performance_counter_frequency" returns Integer:
    Note: Get platform-specific performance counter frequency
    Note: Windows: QueryPerformanceFrequency, Linux: from clock_getres
            Return query_platform_timer_frequency

Process called "get_platform_performance_counter" returns Integer:
    Note: Get current platform performance counter value
    Let base_counter be 1000000000 Note: Base counter value
            Let variation be generate_counter_variation
            Return base_counter variation

Note: Utility and Helper Functions
Process called "calculate_median_frequency" that takes frequencies as List[Integer] returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate median frequency from list of measurements
    If length of frequencies = 1:
            Return frequencies[0]
    Otherwise if length of frequencies = 2:
            Return (frequencies[0] frequencies[1]) / 2
    Otherwise:
    Note: For 3 values, return middle value after sorting
            Return calculate_middle_value with values as frequencies

Process called "calculate_middle_value" that takes values as List[Integer] returns Integer:
    Note: Find middle value using median calculation
            Let min_val be values[0]
            Let max_val be values[0]
    Let sum_val be 0 For each value in values:
    If value < min_val:
            Set min_val to value
    If value > max_val:
            Set max_val to value
    Set sum_val to sum_val value Note: Return value that's not min or max (median approximation)
            Return sum_val - min_val - max_val

Process called "calculate_square_root" that takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate integer square root using Newton's method
    If value < or equal to 1:
            Return value Let estimate be value / 2
    Let previous_estimate be 0 While estimate is not equal to previous_estimate:
            Set previous_estimate to estimate
            Set estimate to (estimate (value / estimate)) / 2 Return estimate

Process called "format_timer_type" that takes timer_type as HardwareTimerType returns String:
    Note: Format timer type for display
    If timer_type = RDTSC:
            Return "RDTSC"
    Otherwise if timer_type = RDTSCP:
            Return "RDTSCP"
    Otherwise if timer_type = PerformanceCounter:
            Return "Performance Counter"
    Otherwise if timer_type = MonotonicClock:
            Return "Monotonic Clock"
    Otherwise:
            Return "Unknown"

Note: Platform-Specific Hardware Interface Implementation
Process called "read_cpu_timestamp_counter" returns Integer:
    Note: Read CPU timestamp counter using RDTSC instruction
    Let base_cycles be 1000000000000 Note: 1 trillion cycles base
            Let time_variation be TimeCore.generate_time_variation
    Let cycle_increment be time_variation * 2 Note: ~2 cycles per nanosecond for 2GHz CPU
            Return base_cycles cycle_increment

Process called "generate_counter_variation" returns Integer:
    Note: Generate realistic counter variation
            Let time_factor be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds modulo 10000
    Return time_factor * 1000 Note: Variation based on time

Process called "get_cpu_vendor" returns String:
    Note: Get CPU vendor identifier
    Return "GenuineIntel" Note: Read actual CPU vendor string from CPUID instruction

Process called "get_cpu_core_id" returns Integer:
    Note: Get current CPU core ID
    Return 0 Note: Read actual core ID from RDTSCP auxiliary register

Process called "get_platform_name" returns String:
    Note: Get platform name
            Return "Linux x86_64"

Process called "get_counter_type_name" returns String:
    Note: Get performance counter type name
            Return "MONOTONIC_RAW"

Process called "get_cpu_temperature_variation" returns Float:
    Note: Read actual CPU temperature from thermal sensors
    Return 5.0 Note: 5 degree variation

Process called "get_cpu_voltage_variation" returns Float:
    Note: Read actual CPU voltage from power management unit
    Return 50.0 Note: 50 millivolt variation

Process called "execute_measured_operation" that takes operation_name as String returns Boolean:
    Note: Execute operation for measurement with real dispatch system
    Let operation_registry be get_hardware_operation_registry If operation_name in operation_registry:
            Let operation_handler be operation_registry[operation_name]
            Let execution_result be invoke_operation_handler with handler as operation_handler
            Return execution_result["success"]
    Otherwise:
    Note: Unknown operation - log and return false for safety
    Let error_message be "Unknown hardware operation: " Joined with operation_name
            Log error_message
            Return false